2
0:0:1,61 --> 0:0:3,14
MALE SPEAKER:
Welcome, everybody.


3
0:0:3,14 --> 0:0:7,62
Six days ago, astronaut
Mark Whatrey--


4
0:0:7,62 --> 0:0:8,37
ANDY WEIR: Watney.


5
0:0:8,37 --> 0:0:10,42
MALE SPEAKER: --became
one of the first men


6
0:0:10,42 --> 0:0:12,92
to walk on the surface of Mars.


7
0:0:12,92 --> 0:0:16,39
Now he may be the
first man to die there.


8
0:0:16,39 --> 0:0:18,87
Will he?


9
0:0:18,87 --> 0:0:22,4
Andy Weir's brilliant
debut novel, "The Martian,"


10
0:0:22,4 --> 0:0:26,92
is a gripping story of
survival against all odds.


11
0:0:26,92 --> 0:0:29,48
The astronaut is stranded
millions of miles


12
0:0:29,48 --> 0:0:32,31
from the nearest human
being with no way


13
0:0:32,31 --> 0:0:35,45
to even signal Earth
that he is alive.


14
0:0:35,45 --> 0:0:37,45
And even if you he
could get word out,


15
0:0:37,45 --> 0:0:40,6
his food would be gone years
before a rescue mission could


16
0:0:40,6 --> 0:0:43,23
arrive.


17
0:0:43,23 --> 0:0:46,94
Andy Weir, he's our neighbor
here in Mountain View,


18
0:0:46,94 --> 0:0:48,45
a longtime programmer.


19
0:0:48,45 --> 0:0:53,88
He got his first job at 15 years
of age at Sandia National Labs.


20
0:0:53,88 --> 0:0:58,3
He wrote code for Warcraft II.


21
0:0:58,3 --> 0:1:1,1
And he's now working
at MobileIron,


22
0:1:1,1 --> 0:1:4,129
where he's working
on Android codes.


23
0:1:4,129 --> 0:1:8,25
And actually, we talked a little
bit how he likes the platform,


24
0:1:8,25 --> 0:1:12,11
and he didn't have
too many complaints.


25
0:1:12,11 --> 0:1:16,37
I guess this is kudos to you
guys from the Android group.


26
0:1:16,37 --> 0:1:23,8
I am pleased to present
the book, "The Martian."


27
0:1:23,8 --> 0:1:25,92
Andy will be talking
to us today about it


28
0:1:25,92 --> 0:1:29,14
and showing some of the
technical details that


29
0:1:29,14 --> 0:1:30,46
went into the book.


30
0:1:30,46 --> 0:1:31,96
And please give a warm welcome.


31
0:1:31,96 --> 0:1:38,39
[APPLAUSE]


32
0:1:38,39 --> 0:1:40,487
ANDY WEIR: So, like he
said, I'm Andy Weir.


33
0:1:40,487 --> 0:1:41,57
And I wrote "The Martian."


34
0:1:41,57 --> 0:1:45,177
I'm going to be talking
to you about that today.


35
0:1:45,177 --> 0:1:47,26
When they told me that I'd
be doing a Google Talk,


36
0:1:47,26 --> 0:1:48,91
they said, you're
going to want to make


37
0:1:48,91 --> 0:1:50,82
about 40 minutes of content.


38
0:1:50,82 --> 0:1:53,91
I don't think I'm going to
make 40 minutes of content.


39
0:1:53,91 --> 0:1:56,85
But I'll just say what I have
to say until I'm out of stuff


40
0:1:56,85 --> 0:2:0,57
to say, and then
I'll take questions.


41
0:2:0,57 --> 0:2:2,5
So you just got the
summary of the book.


42
0:2:2,5 --> 0:2:3,32
But I'm going to do a reading.


43
0:2:3,32 --> 0:2:4,49
I'm going to start us
off with a reading.


44
0:2:4,49 --> 0:2:5,82
And then I'm going to
start talking about some


45
0:2:5,82 --> 0:2:8,52
of the technical stuff that
went into making the book.


46
0:2:8,52 --> 0:2:11,0
The reading's going to
be about 10 minutes.


47
0:2:11,0 --> 0:2:14,41
And it's just the first chapter.


48
0:2:14,41 --> 0:2:17,62
So it's about four
or five pages.


49
0:2:17,62 --> 0:2:20,35
Also, the reading will
include profanities.


50
0:2:20,35 --> 0:2:21,67
I hope nobody's
bothered by that.


51
0:2:21,67 --> 0:2:23,56
I don't see any
children out there.


52
0:2:23,56 --> 0:2:27,63
So I'm just going
to jump right in.


53
0:2:27,63 --> 0:2:29,68
Log entry, Sol 6.


54
0:2:29,68 --> 0:2:31,15
I'm pretty much fucked.


55
0:2:31,15 --> 0:2:32,57
That's my considered opinion.


56
0:2:32,57 --> 0:2:33,94
Fucked.


57
0:2:33,94 --> 0:2:35,76
Six days into what should be the
greatest two months of my life,


58
0:2:35,76 --> 0:2:37,38
and it's turned
into a nightmare.


59
0:2:37,38 --> 0:2:38,53
I don't even know
who'll read this.


60
0:2:38,53 --> 0:2:40,196
I guess someone will
find it eventually,


61
0:2:40,196 --> 0:2:41,42
maybe 100 years from now.


62
0:2:41,42 --> 0:2:43,506
For the record, I
didn't die on Sol 6.


63
0:2:43,506 --> 0:2:45,38
Certainly the rest of
the crew thought I did.


64
0:2:45,38 --> 0:2:46,374
And I can't blame them.


65
0:2:46,374 --> 0:2:48,54
Maybe there'll be a day of
national mourning for me.


66
0:2:48,54 --> 0:2:50,29
And my Wikipedia page
will say Mark Watney


67
0:2:50,29 --> 0:2:52,65
is the only human being
to have died on Mars.


68
0:2:52,65 --> 0:2:53,87
And it'll be right, probably.


69
0:2:53,87 --> 0:2:55,17
Because I'll surely die here.


70
0:2:55,17 --> 0:2:57,78
Just not on Sol 6 when
everyone thinks I did.


71
0:2:57,78 --> 0:2:58,33
Let's see.


72
0:2:58,33 --> 0:2:59,57
Where do I begin?


73
0:2:59,57 --> 0:3:2,37
The Ares program-- mankind
reaching out to Mars


74
0:3:2,37 --> 0:3:4,37
to send people to another
planet for the very first time


75
0:3:4,37 --> 0:3:6,972
and expand the horizons of
humanity, blah, blah, blah.


76
0:3:6,972 --> 0:3:9,18
The Ares 1 crew did their
thing and came back heroes.


77
0:3:9,18 --> 0:3:11,58
They got the parades and
fame and love of the world.


78
0:3:11,58 --> 0:3:13,999
Ares 2 did the same thing in
a different location on Mars.


79
0:3:13,999 --> 0:3:16,4
They got a firm handshake
and a hot cup of coffee


80
0:3:16,4 --> 0:3:17,3
when they got home.


81
0:3:17,3 --> 0:3:18,3
Ares 3?


82
0:3:18,3 --> 0:3:19,23
Well, that's my mission.


83
0:3:19,23 --> 0:3:20,37
Well, not mine, per se.


84
0:3:20,37 --> 0:3:21,62
Commander Lewis was in charge.


85
0:3:21,62 --> 0:3:23,16
I was just one of her crew.


86
0:3:23,16 --> 0:3:25,642
Actually, I was the very lowest
ranked member of the crew.


87
0:3:25,642 --> 0:3:27,35
I would only be in
command of the mission


88
0:3:27,35 --> 0:3:28,86
if I were the only
remaining person.


89
0:3:28,86 --> 0:3:29,776
Hey, what do you know?


90
0:3:29,776 --> 0:3:31,4
I'm in command.


91
0:3:31,4 --> 0:3:32,9
I wonder if this
log'll be recovered


92
0:3:32,9 --> 0:3:34,749
before the rest of the
crew die of old age.


93
0:3:34,749 --> 0:3:36,54
I presume they got back
to Earth all right.


94
0:3:36,54 --> 0:3:38,46
Guys, if you're reading
this, it wasn't your fault.


95
0:3:38,46 --> 0:3:39,66
You did what you had to do.


96
0:3:39,66 --> 0:3:41,63
In your position, I would
have done the same thing.


97
0:3:41,63 --> 0:3:42,34
I don't blame you.


98
0:3:42,34 --> 0:3:43,423
And I'm glad you survived.


99
0:3:43,423 --> 0:3:45,782



100
0:3:45,782 --> 0:3:47,74
I guess I should explain
how Mars missions work


101
0:3:47,74 --> 0:3:49,58
for any laymen who
may be reading this.


102
0:3:49,58 --> 0:3:52,121
We got to Earth orbit the normal
way through an ordinary ship


103
0:3:52,121 --> 0:3:52,914
to "Hermes."


104
0:3:52,914 --> 0:3:54,33
All the Ares
missions use "Hermes"


105
0:3:54,33 --> 0:3:55,48
to get to and from Mars.


106
0:3:55,48 --> 0:3:58,754
It's really big and it cost a
lot, so NASA only built one.


107
0:3:58,754 --> 0:4:1,17
Once we got to "Hermes," four
additional unmanned missions


108
0:4:1,17 --> 0:4:3,52
brought us fuel and supplies
while we prepared for our trip.


109
0:4:3,52 --> 0:4:5,52
Once everything was a
"go," we set out for Mars,


110
0:4:5,52 --> 0:4:6,594
but not very fast.


111
0:4:6,594 --> 0:4:8,26
Gone are the days of
heavy chemical fuel


112
0:4:8,26 --> 0:4:10,32
burns and trans-Mars
injection orbits.


113
0:4:10,32 --> 0:4:11,792
"Hermes" is powered
by ion engines.


114
0:4:11,792 --> 0:4:13,5
They throw argon out
the back of the ship


115
0:4:13,5 --> 0:4:15,93
really fast to get a tiny
amount of acceleration.


116
0:4:15,93 --> 0:4:18,79
The thing is it doesn't
take much reactant mass.


117
0:4:18,79 --> 0:4:20,94
So a little argon and a
nuclear reactor to power things


118
0:4:20,94 --> 0:4:23,261
let us accelerate constantly
the whole way there.


119
0:4:23,261 --> 0:4:24,76
You'd be amazed how
fast you can get


120
0:4:24,76 --> 0:4:27,762
going with a tiny
acceleration over a long time.


121
0:4:27,762 --> 0:4:29,97
I could regale you with
tales of how we had great fun


122
0:4:29,97 --> 0:4:31,132
on the trip, but I won't.


123
0:4:31,132 --> 0:4:32,84
I don't feel like
re-living it right now.


124
0:4:32,84 --> 0:4:35,8
Suffice it to say we
got to Mars 124 days


125
0:4:35,8 --> 0:4:36,97
later without
strangling each other.


126
0:4:36,97 --> 0:4:39,56
From there we took the
MDV, Mars Descent Vehicle,


127
0:4:39,56 --> 0:4:40,56
to the surface.


128
0:4:40,56 --> 0:4:42,98
The MDV is basically a big
can with some light thrusters


129
0:4:42,98 --> 0:4:44,1
and parachutes attached.


130
0:4:44,1 --> 0:4:46,32
Its sole purpose is to get
six humans from Mars orbit


131
0:4:46,32 --> 0:4:48,199
to the surface without
killing any of them.


132
0:4:48,199 --> 0:4:50,49
And now we come to the real
trick of Mars exploration--


133
0:4:50,49 --> 0:4:52,37
having all your shit
there in advance.


134
0:4:52,37 --> 0:4:54,85
A total of 14 unmanned
missions deposited everything


135
0:4:54,85 --> 0:4:56,392
we would need for
surface operations.


136
0:4:56,392 --> 0:4:58,183
They tried their best
to land on the supply


137
0:4:58,183 --> 0:5:0,819
vessels in the same general area
and did a reasonably good job.


138
0:5:0,819 --> 0:5:2,61
Supplies aren't nearly
so fragile as humans


139
0:5:2,61 --> 0:5:4,17
and can hit the
ground really hard,


140
0:5:4,17 --> 0:5:5,829
but they tend to
bounce around a lot.


141
0:5:5,829 --> 0:5:7,37
Naturally they didn't
send us to Mars


142
0:5:7,37 --> 0:5:9,16
until they confirmed that
all the supplies had made it


143
0:5:9,16 --> 0:5:11,368
to the surface and their
containers weren't breached.


144
0:5:11,368 --> 0:5:13,33
Start to finish,
including supply missions,


145
0:5:13,33 --> 0:5:15,52
a Mars mission takes
about three years.


146
0:5:15,52 --> 0:5:17,89
In fact, there were Ares 3
supplies en route to Mars


147
0:5:17,89 --> 0:5:20,441
while the Ares 2 crew
were on their way home.


148
0:5:20,441 --> 0:5:22,94
The most important piece of the
advance supplies, of course,


149
0:5:22,94 --> 0:5:25,314
was the MAV, the
Mars Ascent Vehicle.


150
0:5:25,314 --> 0:5:26,98
That's how we would
get back to "Hermes"


151
0:5:26,98 --> 0:5:28,72
after surface operations
were complete.


152
0:5:28,72 --> 0:5:31,7
The MAV was soft landed
as opposed to the balloon


153
0:5:31,7 --> 0:5:32,705
bounce fest the
other supplies had.


154
0:5:32,705 --> 0:5:35,8
Of course, it was in constant
communication with Houston,


155
0:5:35,8 --> 0:5:36,91
and if there had been
any problems with it,


156
0:5:36,91 --> 0:5:39,77
we would have passed by Mars and
gone home without ever landing.


157
0:5:39,77 --> 0:5:41,7
The MAV is pretty cool.


158
0:5:41,7 --> 0:5:42,93
It turns out through a neat
set of chemical reactions


159
0:5:42,93 --> 0:5:45,388
with the Martian atmosphere,
for every kilogram of hydrogen


160
0:5:45,388 --> 0:5:48,74
you bring to Mars, you can
make 13 kilograms of fuel.


161
0:5:48,74 --> 0:5:49,24
It's a slow process, though.


162
0:5:49,24 --> 0:5:51,5
It takes 24 months
to fill the tank.


163
0:5:51,5 --> 0:5:53,29
That's why they sent it
long before we got there.


164
0:5:53,29 --> 0:5:54,706
You can imagine
how disappointed I


165
0:5:54,706 --> 0:5:57,352
was when I discovered
the MAV was gone.


166
0:5:57,352 --> 0:5:59,56
It was a ridiculous sequence
of events that led to me


167
0:5:59,56 --> 0:6:1,851
almost dying, and an even
more ridiculous sequence that


168
0:6:1,851 --> 0:6:2,77
led to me surviving.


169
0:6:2,77 --> 0:6:4,144
The mission is
designed to handle


170
0:6:4,144 --> 0:6:6,539
sandstorm gusts
of up to 150 KPH.


171
0:6:6,539 --> 0:6:8,8
So Houston got
understandably nervous


172
0:6:8,8 --> 0:6:10,67
when we got whacked
with 175 KPH winds.


173
0:6:10,67 --> 0:6:12,42
We all got in our
flight suits and huddled


174
0:6:12,42 --> 0:6:14,711
in the middle of the Hab just
in case it lost pressure.


175
0:6:14,711 --> 0:6:16,18
But they Hab wasn't the problem.


176
0:6:16,18 --> 0:6:17,289
The MAV is a spaceship.


177
0:6:17,289 --> 0:6:18,58
It has a lot of delicate parts.


178
0:6:18,58 --> 0:6:20,496
It can put up with storms
to a certain extent,


179
0:6:20,496 --> 0:6:22,34
but it can't just get
sand blasted forever.


180
0:6:22,34 --> 0:6:24,131
After an hour and a
half of sustained wind,


181
0:6:24,131 --> 0:6:25,34
NASA gave the order to abort.


182
0:6:25,34 --> 0:6:27,547
Nobody wanted to stop a
month-long mission after only


183
0:6:27,547 --> 0:6:29,68
six days, but if the MAV
took any more punishment,


184
0:6:29,68 --> 0:6:32,35
we'd have all gotten
stranded down there.


185
0:6:32,35 --> 0:6:34,96
We had to go out in the storm
to get from the Hab to the MAV.


186
0:6:34,96 --> 0:6:36,251
And that was going to be risky.


187
0:6:36,251 --> 0:6:37,59
But what choice did we have?


188
0:6:37,59 --> 0:6:39,29
Everyone made it but me.


189
0:6:39,29 --> 0:6:41,52
Our main communications
dish, which relayed signals


190
0:6:41,52 --> 0:6:43,68
from the Hab to "Hermes,"
acted like a parachute getting


191
0:6:43,68 --> 0:6:45,94
torn from its foundation and
carried with the torrent.


192
0:6:45,94 --> 0:6:47,77
Along the way, it crashed
through the reception antenna


193
0:6:47,77 --> 0:6:48,299
array.


194
0:6:48,299 --> 0:6:49,84
Then one of those
long, thin antennae


195
0:6:49,84 --> 0:6:51,27
slammed into me end first.


196
0:6:51,27 --> 0:6:53,54
It tore through my suit like
a bullet through butter.


197
0:6:53,54 --> 0:6:56,494
And I felt the worst pain in my
life as it ripped open my side.


198
0:6:56,494 --> 0:6:58,41
I vaguely remember having
the wind knocked out


199
0:6:58,41 --> 0:6:59,91
of me-- pulled out
of me, really--


200
0:6:59,91 --> 0:7:1,785
and my ears popping
painfully is the pressure


201
0:7:1,785 --> 0:7:2,63
in my suit escaped.


202
0:7:2,63 --> 0:7:4,546
The last thing I remember
was seeing Johanssen


203
0:7:4,546 --> 0:7:6,68
hopelessly reaching
out toward me.


204
0:7:6,68 --> 0:7:8,52
I awoke to an oxygen
alarm in my suit,


205
0:7:8,52 --> 0:7:10,27
a steady obnoxious
beeping that aroused me


206
0:7:10,27 --> 0:7:14,66
from a deep and profound
desire to just fucking die.


207
0:7:14,66 --> 0:7:15,56
The storm had abated.


208
0:7:15,56 --> 0:7:17,8
I was face down, almost
totally buried in sand.


209
0:7:17,8 --> 0:7:19,21
As I groggily came
to, I wondered


210
0:7:19,21 --> 0:7:21,119
why I wasn't more dead.


211
0:7:21,119 --> 0:7:22,66
The antenna had
enough force to punch


212
0:7:22,66 --> 0:7:24,2
through the suit
and my side, but it


213
0:7:24,2 --> 0:7:25,31
had been stopped by my pelvis.


214
0:7:25,31 --> 0:7:26,976
So there was only one
hole in the suit--


215
0:7:26,976 --> 0:7:29,43
and a hole in me, of course.


216
0:7:29,43 --> 0:7:30,9
I'd been knocked
back quite a ways


217
0:7:30,9 --> 0:7:32,108
and rolled down a steep hill.


218
0:7:32,108 --> 0:7:33,49
Somehow I landed
face down, which


219
0:7:33,49 --> 0:7:35,62
forced the antenna into a
strongly oblique angle that


220
0:7:35,62 --> 0:7:37,453
put a lot of torque on
the hole in the suit.


221
0:7:37,453 --> 0:7:38,61
It made a weak seal.


222
0:7:38,61 --> 0:7:40,11
Then the copious
blood from my wound


223
0:7:40,11 --> 0:7:41,23
trickled down toward the hole.


224
0:7:41,23 --> 0:7:43,2
As the blood reached the site
of the breach, the water in it


225
0:7:43,2 --> 0:7:45,7
quickly evaporated from the
air flow and low pressure,


226
0:7:45,7 --> 0:7:47,374
leaving a gunky residue behind.


227
0:7:47,374 --> 0:7:49,79
More blood came in behind it
and was also reduced to gunk.


228
0:7:49,79 --> 0:7:51,45
Eventually it sealed
the gaps around the hole


229
0:7:51,45 --> 0:7:52,824
and reduced the
leak to something


230
0:7:52,824 --> 0:7:54,68
the suit could counteract.


231
0:7:54,68 --> 0:7:56,374
The suit did its job admirably.


232
0:7:56,374 --> 0:7:58,165
Sensing the drop in
pressure, it constantly


233
0:7:58,165 --> 0:8:0,584
flooded itself with air from
my nitrogen tank to equalize.


234
0:8:0,584 --> 0:8:2,25
Once the leak became
manageable, it only


235
0:8:2,25 --> 0:8:5,4
had to trickle new air in
slowly to relieve the air lost.


236
0:8:5,4 --> 0:8:7,989
After a while, the CO2, carbon
dioxide, absorbers in the suit


237
0:8:7,989 --> 0:8:10,28
were expended That's really
the limiting factor to life


238
0:8:10,28 --> 0:8:12,53
support-- not the amount of
oxygen you bring with you,


239
0:8:12,53 --> 0:8:14,34
but the amount of
CO2 you can remove.


240
0:8:14,34 --> 0:8:16,62
In the Hab, I have the
oxygenator, a large piece


241
0:8:16,62 --> 0:8:20,284
of equipment that breaks apart
CO2 to give the oxygen back.


242
0:8:20,284 --> 0:8:21,95
But the space suits
have to be portable.


243
0:8:21,95 --> 0:8:23,79
So they use a simple
chemical absorption


244
0:8:23,79 --> 0:8:25,58
process with expendable filters.


245
0:8:25,58 --> 0:8:28,304
I'd been asleep long enough
that my filters were useless.


246
0:8:28,304 --> 0:8:30,72
The suit saw this problem and
moved into an emergency mode


247
0:8:30,72 --> 0:8:32,309
the engineers call
"bloodletting."


248
0:8:32,309 --> 0:8:33,929
Having no way to
separate the CO2,


249
0:8:33,929 --> 0:8:36,47
the suit deliberately vented
air into the Martian atmosphere,


250
0:8:36,47 --> 0:8:37,94
then back-filled with nitrogen.


251
0:8:37,94 --> 0:8:39,34
Between the breach
and the bloodletting,


252
0:8:39,34 --> 0:8:40,659
it quickly ran out of nitrogen.


253
0:8:40,659 --> 0:8:42,846
All it had left
was my oxygen tank.


254
0:8:42,846 --> 0:8:44,97
So it did the only thing
it could to keep me alive.


255
0:8:44,97 --> 0:8:46,678
It started back-filling
with pure oxygen.


256
0:8:46,678 --> 0:8:49,84
I now risked dying
from oxygen toxicity


257
0:8:49,84 --> 0:8:50,75
as the excessively
high amount of oxygen


258
0:8:50,75 --> 0:8:53,25
threatened to burn up my nervous
system, lungs, and eyes--


259
0:8:53,25 --> 0:8:55,791
an ironic death for someone with
a leaky space suit, too much


260
0:8:55,791 --> 0:8:56,571
oxygen.


261
0:8:56,571 --> 0:8:59,7
Every step of the way would
have had beeping alarms, alerts,


262
0:8:59,7 --> 0:8:59,63
and warnings.


263
0:8:59,63 --> 0:9:2,55
But it was a high oxygen
morning that woke me.


264
0:9:2,55 --> 0:9:4,68
The sheer volume of training for
a space mission is astounding.


265
0:9:4,68 --> 0:9:7,2
I'd spent a week back on Earth
practicing emergency spacesuit


266
0:9:7,2 --> 0:9:7,7
drills.


267
0:9:7,7 --> 0:9:8,622
I knew what to do.


268
0:9:8,622 --> 0:9:10,33
Carefully reaching
the side of my helmet,


269
0:9:10,33 --> 0:9:11,22
I got the breach kit.


270
0:9:11,22 --> 0:9:13,49
It's nothing more than a funnel
with a valve at the small end


271
0:9:13,49 --> 0:9:15,78
and an unbelievably sticky
resin on the white end.


272
0:9:15,78 --> 0:9:18,284
The idea is you have
the valve open and stick


273
0:9:18,284 --> 0:9:19,45
the white end over the hole.


274
0:9:19,45 --> 0:9:20,71
The air can escape
through the valve


275
0:9:20,71 --> 0:9:22,9
so it doesn't interfere with
the resin making a good seal.


276
0:9:22,9 --> 0:9:24,92
Then you close the valve,
and you've sealed the breach.


277
0:9:24,92 --> 0:9:26,99
The tricky part was getting
the antenna out of the way.


278
0:9:26,99 --> 0:9:28,29
I pulled it out as
fast as I could,


279
0:9:28,29 --> 0:9:30,581
wincing as the sudden pressure
drop dizzied me and made


280
0:9:30,581 --> 0:9:32,649
the wound in my side
scream in agony.


281
0:9:32,649 --> 0:9:34,69
I got the breach kit over
the hole and sealed it.


282
0:9:34,69 --> 0:9:35,32
It held.


283
0:9:35,32 --> 0:9:37,96
The suit back-filled the missing
air with yet more oxygen.


284
0:9:37,96 --> 0:9:41,1
Checking my arm readouts, I saw
the suit was now at 85% oxygen.


285
0:9:41,1 --> 0:9:43,69
For reference, Earth's
atmosphere is about 21%.


286
0:9:43,69 --> 0:9:46,69
I'd be OK so long as I didn't
spend too much time like that.


287
0:9:46,69 --> 0:9:48,47
I stumbled up the
hill back to the Hab.


288
0:9:48,47 --> 0:9:49,81
As I crested the
rise, I saw something


289
0:9:49,81 --> 0:9:51,351
that made me very
happy and something


290
0:9:51,351 --> 0:9:52,27
that made me very sad.


291
0:9:52,27 --> 0:9:53,31
The Hab was intact.


292
0:9:53,31 --> 0:9:53,9
Yay!


293
0:9:53,9 --> 0:9:55,5
And the MAV was gone.


294
0:9:55,5 --> 0:9:55,505
Boo!


295
0:9:55,505 --> 0:9:58,729



296
0:9:58,729 --> 0:10:0,52
Right at that moment,
I knew I was screwed.


297
0:10:0,52 --> 0:10:2,2
But I didn't want to just
die out on the surface.


298
0:10:2,2 --> 0:10:4,5
I limped back to the Hab
and fumbled my way out


299
0:10:4,5 --> 0:10:5,56
into an airlock.


300
0:10:5,56 --> 0:10:7,552
As soon as it equalized,
I threw off my helmet.


301
0:10:7,552 --> 0:10:9,135
Once inside the Hab,
I doffed the suit


302
0:10:9,135 --> 0:10:10,922
and got my first good
look at the injury.


303
0:10:10,922 --> 0:10:11,88
It would need stitches.


304
0:10:11,88 --> 0:10:13,504
Fortunately, all of
us had been trained


305
0:10:13,504 --> 0:10:16,0
in basic medical
procedures and the Hab


306
0:10:16,0 --> 0:10:17,819
had excellent medical supplies.


307
0:10:17,819 --> 0:10:20,11
A quick shot of a local
anesthetic, irrigate the wound,


308
0:10:20,11 --> 0:10:21,44
nine stitches, and I was done.


309
0:10:21,44 --> 0:10:23,44
I'd be taking antibiotics
for a couple of weeks,


310
0:10:23,44 --> 0:10:24,774
but other than that I'd be fine.


311
0:10:24,774 --> 0:10:26,523
I knew it was hopeless,
but I tried firing


312
0:10:26,523 --> 0:10:27,72
up the communications array.


313
0:10:27,72 --> 0:10:28,704
No signal, of course.


314
0:10:28,704 --> 0:10:30,87
The primary satellite dish
had broken off, remember?


315
0:10:30,87 --> 0:10:33,26
And it took the reception
antennae with it.


316
0:10:33,26 --> 0:10:35,66
The Hab had secondary and
tertiary communication systems,


317
0:10:35,66 --> 0:10:37,118
but they were both
just for talking


318
0:10:37,118 --> 0:10:39,63
to the MAV, which would use
it's much more powerful systems


319
0:10:39,63 --> 0:10:40,505
to relay to "Hermes."


320
0:10:40,505 --> 0:10:43,42
The thing is, that only works
if the MAV is still around.


321
0:10:43,42 --> 0:10:44,87
I had no way to
talk to "Hermes."


322
0:10:44,87 --> 0:10:46,61
In time, I could locate
the dish on the surface,


323
0:10:46,61 --> 0:10:48,42
but it would take weeks for
me to rig up any repairs


324
0:10:48,42 --> 0:10:49,544
and that would be too late.


325
0:10:49,544 --> 0:10:52,134
In an abort, "Hermes" would
leave within 24 hours.


326
0:10:52,134 --> 0:10:54,3
The orbital dynamics made
the trip safer and shorter


327
0:10:54,3 --> 0:10:55,26
the earlier you left.


328
0:10:55,26 --> 0:10:56,566
So why wait?


329
0:10:56,566 --> 0:10:58,19
Checking out my suit,
I saw the antenna


330
0:10:58,19 --> 0:10:59,91
had plowed through my
biomonitor computer.


331
0:10:59,91 --> 0:11:1,421
When on an EVA, all
the crew's suits


332
0:11:1,421 --> 0:11:3,42
are networked so we can
see each other's status.


333
0:11:3,42 --> 0:11:5,55
The rest of the crew would have
seen the pressure in my suit


334
0:11:5,55 --> 0:11:7,216
drop to nearly zero
followed immediately


335
0:11:7,216 --> 0:11:9,9
by my biosigns going flat.


336
0:11:9,9 --> 0:11:11,477
Add to that, watching me
tumble down a hill with a spear


337
0:11:11,477 --> 0:11:13,6
threw me in the
middle of a sandstorm?


338
0:11:13,6 --> 0:11:14,46
Yeah, they thought I was dead.


339
0:11:14,46 --> 0:11:16,192
How could they not?


340
0:11:16,192 --> 0:11:17,9
They may have even
had a brief discussion


341
0:11:17,9 --> 0:11:20,27
about recovering my body,
but regulations were clear.


342
0:11:20,27 --> 0:11:22,737
In the event a crewman dies
on Mars, he stays on Mars.


343
0:11:22,737 --> 0:11:25,32
Leaving his body behind reduces
weight for the MAV on the trip


344
0:11:25,32 --> 0:11:25,69
back.


345
0:11:25,69 --> 0:11:27,815
That means more disposable
fuel and a larger margin


346
0:11:27,815 --> 0:11:29,32
of error for the return thrust.


347
0:11:29,32 --> 0:11:31,64
No point in giving that
up for sentimentality.


348
0:11:31,64 --> 0:11:32,93
So that's the situation.


349
0:11:32,93 --> 0:11:33,84
I'm stranded on Mars.


350
0:11:33,84 --> 0:11:35,65
I have no way to communicate
with "Hermes" or Earth.


351
0:11:35,65 --> 0:11:36,84
Everyone thinks I'm dead.


352
0:11:36,84 --> 0:11:38,86
I'm in a Hab designed
to last 31 days.


353
0:11:38,86 --> 0:11:40,789
If the oxygenator breaks
down, I'll suffocate.


354
0:11:40,789 --> 0:11:43,8
If the water reclaimer breaks
down, I'll die of thirst.


355
0:11:43,8 --> 0:11:45,6
If the Hab breaches, I'll
just kind of explode.


356
0:11:45,6 --> 0:11:46,56
If none of those
things happen, I'll


357
0:11:46,56 --> 0:11:48,518
eventually run out of
food and starve to death.


358
0:11:48,518 --> 0:11:49,743
So yeah, I'm fucked.


359
0:11:49,743 --> 0:11:50,689
[LAUGHTER]


360
0:11:50,689 --> 0:11:56,37
[APPLAUSE]


361
0:11:56,37 --> 0:11:57,78
So that's chapter one.


362
0:11:57,78 --> 0:11:59,895



